10.4.24  1:24 pm   i want to learn romanian, should i go down the youtube route or duolingo?

      this is the method i recommend: find genuine conversational content in the language, with accurate transcriptions. this can be harder to find for more obscure languages, but that is what you need. auto-transcribe is usually not quite good enough to be reliable, so it's better to get something that has been truly and accurately transcribed by a real person. genuine conversational content, by real native speakers (not made-up textbook scenarios, you need real people really talking naturally). then run the transcript through a translator and then just start getting curious about what means what. let your curiosity drive you. maybe even start fixing the mistakes of the transcription. after a few weeks you can start guessing the translation based on the written transcript, and then, after a few months, you can start trying to transcribe just based on the audio alone. in addition to this, continue listening/watching the content casually in your free time. and most importantly, be patient. this will take years. it doesn't take skill, it takes time and curiosity. don't worry about speaking. just keep spending more and more time listening and breaking down what you're hearing, listening, listening more, and eventually after a few years the language will automatically start spilling out of your mouth
